As we enter in the second half of 2025, both USD/CAD and USD/MXN face a landscape shaped by economic uncertainty, trade tensions, and decisions made by central banks. By : Julian Pineda, CFA , Market Analyst Today 1:00 PM 7/4/2025 12:00:00 PM Share this: Within the North American economic bloc, Mexico and Canada’s currencies have played a central role in trade flows and regional financial stability. As we enter in the second half of 2025, both USD/CAD and USD/MXN face a landscape shaped by economic uncertainty, trade tensions, and decisions made by central banks . These factors have influenced their movements in recent months and are likely to remain key drivers for the rest of the year. So far, the Mexican peso and the Canadian dollar have shown a tendency to strengthen , largely fueled by the weakness of the U.S. dollar . The Role of Central Banks At the time of writing, North America's central banks have shown a dovish bias , with rate cuts that began around June 2024. The case of Banco de México stands out , having reduced its interest rate from 11% to 8.0% over the course of a year , making it the only one to implement a sustained easing cycle. This positions Mexico as the country that has most significantly loosened its monetary policy compared to its regional peers. The Bank of Canada has followed a similar path , cutting its rate from 4.75% to 2.75% over the course of 12 months . However, it has recently adopted a more cautious stance , signaling a pause in rate cuts and an intention to keep the policy rate unchanged in the short term , while closely monitoring inflation dynamics. <div class="field-content" data-process-content="true"><p>Within the North American economic bloc, <b>Mexico and Canada’s currencies have played a central role</b> in trade flows and regional financial stability. As we enter in the second half of 2025, both <b>USD/CAD and USD/MXN face a landscape shaped by economic uncertainty, trade tensions, and decisions made by central banks</b>. These factors have influenced their movements in recent months and are likely to remain key drivers for the rest of the year. So far, the <b>Mexican peso and the Canadian dollar have shown a tendency to strengthen</b>, largely fueled by <b>the weakness of the U.S. dollar</b>.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span style="font-size:38px;"><b>The Role of Central Banks</b></span></p>
<p>At the time of writing, <b>North America's central banks have shown a dovish bias</b>, with rate cuts that began around June 2024. The case of <b>Banco de México stands out</b>, having reduced its interest rate from <b>11% to 8.0% over the course of a year</b>, making it the only one to implement a sustained easing cycle. This positions <b>Mexico as the country that has most significantly loosened its monetary policy</b> compared to its regional peers.</p>
<p>The <b>Bank of Canada has followed a similar path</b>, cutting its rate from <b>4.75% to 2.75% over the course of 12 months</b>. However, it has recently adopted a <b>more cautious stance</b>, signaling a pause in rate cuts and an intention to <b>keep the policy rate unchanged in the short term</b>, while closely monitoring inflation dynamics.</p>
<p>The <b>Federal Reserve has taken a different path</b> from the regional trend, with a rate cut from <b>5.5% to 4.5%</b>, which has remained unchanged since the last adjustment in December 2024. Unlike Mexico and Canada, the <b>Fed has not prioritized a low-rate policy</b> and continues to be the <b>most conservative central bank in the bloc</b>, maintaining a firm stance against further cuts, although it remains unclear what direction it will take in the coming months.</p>
<p><b><i>Interest Rate Table – North America (2024–2025)</i></b></p>
<p> </p>
<p><i>Colors: From green to red. Green for higher interest rates and red for lower rates.</i></p>
<p><img alt="" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="28b16b4d-4eff-4c3a-96ba-496cb9adc9ac" height="96" src="https://micms.stonex.com//sites/default/files/inline-images-2/5882/ALLINTERESTRATESTABLEQ3.png" width="700" loading="lazy" class="lightense-target"></p>
<p>Source: Data - Tradingeconomics</p>
<p><b><i>Interest Rate Chart – North American Currencies (2024–2025)</i></b></p>
<p><img alt="" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="10ad6c2a-55f0-47fb-a883-8e11956f9fef" height="284" src="https://micms.stonex.com//sites/default/files/inline-images-2/5882/CHARTallinterestrates.png" width="700" loading="lazy" class="lightense-target"></p>
<p> </p>
<p>Source: Tradingeconomics</p>
<p>The contrast in monetary policies highlights the <b>Fed’s role as the most stable actor within the North American bloc</b>. As Mexico continues its <b>rate-cutting cycle</b> and Canada shifts to a <b>holding pattern</b>, the Federal Reserve has maintained <b>its rate at 4.5% all year</b>, reflecting a more aggressive approach. In this context, where investments in Canada and Mexico typically carry higher risk, a <b>neutral and consistent monetary policy from the Fed may appear more attractive to international investors</b>. This stability in <b>dollar-denominated returns</b> could become a key factor in supporting demand for the U.S. dollar in the coming months and <b>strengthening its position against other currencies</b>, as long as the Fed's steady stance holds.</p>
<p>The big question is <b>how monetary policy will evolve in the coming months</b>, as it will be a <b>decisive factor for the long-term strength of North American currencies</b>:</p>
<ul>
<li>In its <b>June 4 decision</b>, the <b>Bank of Canada stated that it must maintain a cautious stance</b>, given that <b>core inflation remains a risk</b>. However, it left the door open to a <b>further rate cut if the economy weakens</b>, which could bring the <b>interest rate down to 2.5% in the short term</b>.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>On <b>June 26</b>, <b>Banco de México</b> decided to lower the interest rate to <b>8.0%</b>, continuing its series of consecutive cuts. It was even noted that the <b>weakening of economic activity suggests further cuts could take place during the remainder of the year</b>.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>The <b>Federal Reserve maintains a different approach</b>. In its <b>June 18 decision</b>, it reaffirmed its <b>“wait and see” strategy</b>, noting that <b>more evidence of sustained inflation moving toward the 2% target is needed</b>. Until then, the Fed is likely to <b>maintain a more hawkish tone</b> compared to its North American peers.</li>
</ul>
<p>It’s important to remember that <b>inflation dynamics remain a key factor in monetary policy decisions</b> made by central banks.</p>
<p>In <b>Canada</b>, inflation remains stable at <b>1.7% (as of May)</b>, within the <b>2% target</b>. In <b>Mexico</b>, it stands at <b>4.4% (May)</b>, <b>above the 3% target</b>. In the <b>United States</b>, although the target remains at 2%, <b>inflation reached 2.4% in May</b>, still <b>falling short of fully meeting the goal</b>.</p>
<p><b><i>Inflation Trends in North American Countries (2024–2025)</i></b></p>
<p><img alt="" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="0aa0dda8-cde5-42e3-9bb3-11b53880ef5a" height="290" src="https://micms.stonex.com//sites/default/files/inline-images-2/5882/Inflationrates.png" width="700" loading="lazy" class="lightense-target"></p>
<p> </p>
<p>Source: Tradingeconomics</p>
<p>In the long term, the <b>Bank of Canada appears to have more room for a looser policy</b>, thanks to the <b>downward trend in inflation</b>. In contrast, in <b>Mexico and the United States</b>, inflation has once again <b>exceeded expectations</b>, limiting that flexibility.</p>
<p><b>Mexico is prioritizing stimulus over inflation</b>, supporting a stance favoring <b>lower interest rates</b>, while <b>Canada has shifted to a more neutral approach</b> due to <b>contained inflation</b>. However, these <b>dovish outlooks may not necessarily translate into stronger demand for fixed-income securities</b> in either country. In contrast, the <b>Federal Reserve’s rate stability at 4.5%</b>, backed by its <b>firm policy stance</b>, may continue as <b>inflation in the U.S. remains above target</b>, giving the Fed room to <b>keep rates elevated for longer</b>. This could attract capital into <b>U.S. dollar–denominated assets</b>, particularly <b>Treasuries</b>, and as a result, <b>may help strengthen the U.S. dollar</b>. This <b>constant divergence in monetary policy</b> may begin to <b>undermine the buying strength that both the Mexican peso and Canadian dollar have shown throughout the year</b> and <b>could lead to some upside pressure on USD/CAD and USD/MXN</b>.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span style="font-size:38px;"><b>Is the trade war still a relevant factor?</b></span></p>
<p><b>Mexico and Canada still face a 25% tariff imposed by the White House on various products</b>. However, uncertainty has remained under control, as these tariffs mainly affect goods that are <b>not covered under the USMCA agreement</b>. <b>Nevertheless, the risk of a renewed trade war remains present</b>, especially after the Trump administration <b>announced the suspension of trade negotiations with Canada on June 27</b> following a dispute over the digital services tax. Although the conflict was quickly de-escalated and negotiations resumed on June 30, the episode highlighted how quickly tensions can flare up. In this context, even though the market appears to have moved past the latest trade conflict involving Canada and Mexico, <b>there are underlying risks that could reignite friction and undermine the sense of stability</b> that has prevailed in recent months.</p>
<p>It's worth noting that <b>during the trade war, both the Mexican peso and the Canadian dollar have shown strength against the U.S. dollar</b>, which has been weakening since the conflict began. The market fears that the <b>U.S. currency will bear the brunt of the consequences</b>, and this has been reflected in the performance of the <b>DXY index</b>, which tracks the dollar's behavior. The index has recorded <b>steady declines following key developments of the trade war</b>, weakening confidence in the dollar and allowing the <b>peso and the Canadian dollar to gain ground</b>. The DXY has even <b>fallen below the 100-point mark</b>, a level not seen since 2022, confirming the <b>sustained bearish pressure</b> the dollar has faced amid the conflict.</p>
<p><img alt="" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="4138936e-d32b-4eb5-99e0-2e91bf7fda80" height="400" src="https://micms.stonex.com//sites/default/files/inline-images-2/5882/DXY%20English.png" width="700" loading="lazy" class="lightense-target"></p>
<p> </p>
<p>Source: TVC, Tradingview</p>
<p>At the time of writing, <b>there is no clear diplomatic resolution in sight for the trade war initiated by the White House</b>, a conflict that has exposed the <b>high sensitivity of North American currencies</b>. As the United States <b>takes a tougher stance toward the European Union and China</b>, the situation has <b>favored the Mexican peso and the Canadian dollar</b>, driven by <b>growing distrust toward the U.S. dollar</b> due to the potential <b>domestic economic impact of the conflict</b>.</p>
<p>However, in previous phases, when <b>tariff measures were directly aimed at Mexico and Canada</b>, both currencies showed <b>clear weakness</b>, which <b>calls into question the sustainability of their current strength</b>. If <b>no trade agreement is reached to ease uncertainty</b>, <b>confidence in the Mexican peso and the Canadian dollar could deteriorate</b>, while the <b>U.S. dollar</b>, after a <b>prolonged period of weakness</b>, could begin to <b>recover</b>. This would <b>open the door to renewed buying pressure on USD/CAD and USD/MXN</b>, especially if the <b>trade war continues.</b></p>
<p> </p>
<p><span style="font-size:38px;"><b>USD/CAD Outlook</b></span></p>
<p><img alt="" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="aeddd516-f934-4ce9-a1dd-729c797f99c7" height="391" src="https://micms.stonex.com//sites/default/files/inline-images-2/5882/USDCAD%20ENGLISH.png" width="700" loading="lazy" class="lightense-target"></p>
<p> </p>
<p>Source: StoneX, Tradingview</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Long-Term Uptrend:</b> Since <b>May 2021</b>, <b>USD/CAD has maintained an upward trend</b>, which in recent months has weakened due to significant <b>bearish corrections</b>. Although this does not confirm a full reversal, it <b>could lead to a prolonged period of neutrality</b>, like what occurred in 2023. For now, if <b>sellers fail to break decisively below the 100-period moving average</b> and <b>technical signs of buying strength begin to emerge</b>, this dynamic could set the stage for a <b>sideways phase in the pair over the medium to long term</b>.</li>
<li><b>Indicators:</b>
<ul>
<li><b>RSI:</b> The <b>RSI line continues to oscillate below the 50 level</b>, confirming a <b>dominant bearish bias</b> in recent weeks. However, it has started to <b>recover from oversold territory</b>, near the 30 level. If this improvement persists, it could signal a <b>resurgence in buying strength</b> and pave the way for a <b>stronger bullish momentum</b>.</li>
<li><b>MACD:</b> The <b>MACD histogram maintains a mild bearish outlook</b>, oscillating near the <b>neutral zero line</b>, which reflects <b>uncertainty in the moving average trend</b>. If it fails to move decisively away from this area, a <b>neutral movement is likely to take hold</b> in the pair’s technical structure.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><b>Key Levels:</b>
<ul>
<li><b>1.41719 – Key resistance</b>: Located in the <b>neutral zone of recent months</b>, this level coincides with the <b>38.2% Fibonacci retracement</b>. Price action returning to this area could <b>reactivate a bullish bias</b> and restore momentum to the <b>long-term trend</b> that previously dominated the chart structure.</li>
<li><b>1.38410 – Nearby resistance</b>: Positioned in a <b>neutral zone</b> that aligns with the <b>previously broken uptrend</b> and the <b>100-period moving average</b>. As long as the price continues oscillating near this area, it could <b>extend a potential phase of sustained neutrality</b> on the chart.</li>
<li><b>1.34356 – Key support</b>: Located in a <b>critical technical zone marked by the 200-period moving average</b>. If the price breaks below this level, it could <b>trigger a new long-term downtrend</b>, with <b>bearish momentum once again taking control of the market</b>.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p> </p>
<p><span style="font-size:38px;"><b>USD/MXN Outlook</b></span></p>
<p><img alt="" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="f888a26c-1224-4211-9850-f292e1b79633" height="391" src="https://micms.stonex.com//sites/default/files/inline-images-2/5882/USDMXN%20english.png" width="700" loading="lazy" class="lightense-target"></p>
<p> </p>
<p>Source: StoneX, Tradingview</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Downtrend emerges:</b> Since January, <b>USD/MXN has developed a sustained downtrend</b>, with price movements even dipping <b>below 19 pesos per dollar</b>. So far, <b>no significant bullish correction has emerged</b> to threaten the long-term structure, so the overall bias <b>remains bearish</b>. However, the price is now <b>facing key technical barriers</b>, which could pave the way for a <b>more meaningful bullish correction</b> if <b>downward pressure begins to fade</b>.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><b>Indicators:</b><p>
</p><ul>
<li><b>RSI: </b>The <b>RSI line remains below the 50 level</b>, reflecting a <b>dominant bearish bias</b>. However, it is approaching the <b>oversold threshold (30)</b>, which could signal a <b>pause in selling pressure</b> and open the door to <b>bullish corrections that may extend over several weeks</b>.</li>
<li><b>MACD: </b>The <b>MACD shows a sustained neutral signal</b>, with oscillations near the <b>zero line</b>, indicating a <b>pause in the momentum of the moving averages</b>. As long as this behavior in the histogram and MACD lines remains steady, it could lead to a <b>more prolonged period of price neutrality</b>.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><b>Key Levels: </b><p>
</p><ul>
<li><b>19.00 – Close resistance</b>: located in the key area of<b> the 200-period moving average. </b>This level could act as a <b>steady brake on potential bullish corrections</b>, and <b>price movements above this barrier could open the door to a stronger bullish bias</b>.</li>
<li><b>20.00 – Key resistance</b>: This level aligns with the <b>23.6% Fibonacci retracement</b>. <b>Bullish movements approaching this zone could challenge the current bearish structure</b> and pave the way for a <b>dominant long-term bullish bias</b>, if a sustained breakout occurs.</li>
<li><b>18.50 – Final support zone</b>: Located at the <b>100-period moving average</b>, this level coincides with prices not seen since <b>July 2024</b>. If <b>bearish movements reach this level</b>, it could <b>trigger a dominant downtrend</b>, with the potential to <b>extend over several months</b> on the USD/MXN chart.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
